<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Markdown on Henry Techie</title><link>https://namanh11611.github.io/tags/markdown/</link><description>Recent content in Markdown on Henry Techie</description><generator>Hugo -- gohugo.io</generator><language>en</language><lastBuildDate>Sun, 25 Feb 2024 00:00:00 +0700</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://namanh11611.github.io/tags/markdown/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Mermaid - Draw diagrams and charts as easily as candy with Markdown</title><link>https://namanh11611.github.io/p/mermaid/</link><pubDate>Sun, 25 Feb 2024 00:00:00 +0700</pubDate><guid>https://namanh11611.github.io/p/mermaid/</guid><description>&lt;img src="https://namanh11611.github.io/p/mermaid/mermaid.webp" alt="Featured image of post Mermaid - Draw diagrams and charts as easily as candy with Markdown" /&gt;&lt;h1 id="the-old-days"&gt;The Old Days
&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;p&gt;As you know, diagrams and documentation play an important role in projects. They act as a compass to help developers understand the ideas of PMs, tech leads, or BAs, guide the required flow, and serve as evidence for reference when there are disputes about project requirements. A picture is worth a thousand words; sometimes a clear diagram can save hours of explanation and back-and-forth discussion.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Previously, when drawing diagrams for projects, I often used &lt;strong&gt;&lt;a class="link" href="https://app.diagrams.net" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
&gt;draw.io&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;. For those who don&amp;rsquo;t know, it&amp;rsquo;s an online tool for drawing diagrams by &lt;strong&gt;drag and drop&lt;/strong&gt;. But every time I needed to update a diagram, I had to drag and drop each box or arrow again, which was quite time-consuming. Until one day, a colleague introduced me to &lt;strong&gt;Mermaid&lt;/strong&gt;, and everything changed&amp;hellip;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h1 id="enlightened-by-mermaid"&gt;Enlightened by Mermaid
&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;p&gt;According to the definition on the official website, &lt;strong&gt;&lt;a class="link" href="https://mermaid.js.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
&gt;Mermaid&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; is a tool built on &lt;strong&gt;JavaScript&lt;/strong&gt; that helps create &lt;strong&gt;diagrams&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;charts&lt;/strong&gt; flexibly from &lt;strong&gt;text&lt;/strong&gt; with syntax similar to &lt;strong&gt;Markdown&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src="https://namanh11611.github.io/p/mermaid/mermaid.webp"
width="1170"
height="497"
srcset="https://namanh11611.github.io/p/mermaid/mermaid_hu_8d18830431e94328.webp 480w, https://namanh11611.github.io/p/mermaid/mermaid_hu_868de9c6e0f3cf0f.webp 1024w"
loading="lazy"
alt="Mermaid"
class="gallery-image"
data-flex-grow="235"
data-flex-basis="564px"
&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id="advantages"&gt;Advantages
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;This is an open-source and completely free tool. It supports many popular types of diagrams and charts such as &lt;strong&gt;Flowchart&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;Sequence diagram&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;Class diagram&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;State diagram&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;Git graph&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;hellip;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The syntax is very simple and easy to learn. If you&amp;rsquo;re already familiar with Markdown, you just need to spend a little time to master it. Now, whenever project requirements change, you only need to edit a few lines of text and the diagram will be updated quickly.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For simple diagrams, you can use &lt;strong&gt;&lt;a class="link" href="https://mermaid.live" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
&gt;Mermaid Live Editor&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; without installing anything. For company projects, Mermaid is already integrated with &lt;strong&gt;Notion&lt;/strong&gt; or &lt;strong&gt;Atlassian&lt;/strong&gt; products. If you want to use it locally, Mermaid works right in popular IDEs like &lt;strong&gt;Visual Studio Code&lt;/strong&gt; or JetBrains family.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id="comparison-with-plantuml"&gt;Comparison with PlantUML
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;There are other tools on the market that render diagrams from text like Mermaid, the most notable being &lt;strong&gt;&lt;a class="link" href="https://plantuml.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
&gt;PlantUML&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;. Below is a comparison table for an overview.&lt;/p&gt;
